<br>
As Millikin was demonstrating a technique for hunting in a tundra environment to another Northman shaman she met recently named Tindaila, an abrupt mental mandate distracted her attention and the snow leopard she had been stalking, moved out of sight.<br>
 &quot;That medallion you have.  I'll take it off your hands.&quot;  The demanding tone was unmistakably Valdayana D`Varr's.  <br>
 &quot;What medallion?&quot;  Millikin's expression was blank.  She specifically remembered that she had at least three medallions in her possession and the arrogant enchanter's presumptuous manner immediately annoyed the ranger.  A sudden warcry from one of Tindaila's companions as he drove his spear into a mammoth diverted Millikin's attention to the hunt.  She watched the group, occasionally reciting a cantra to heal them if they were seriously injured but after a few moments the mammoth collapsed into the snow, dead -- killed when Tindaila delivered a crushing blow right between the mammoth's eyes.  The snowy ground reverberated from the beast's sudden impact.<br>
 &quot;The one Dermonar let you have from that skeleton that roams near Fironia Vie.&quot;  Unless Millikin's perceptions were off, she thought she detected a hint of annoyance at having to elaborate on something that should be elementary to the ranger.  'Let me have?...'  All of a sudden her attention was undivided from Valdayana's words.  Time to clarify something.  <br>
 &quot;One, I helped kill that skeleton.  Dermonar didn't give it to me.  Two, how do you know about it?&quot;<br>
The two of them had obtained the medal for Exilia and Millikin volunteered to deliver it, only to find out Exilia didn't need it any longer.  The ranger had all but forgotten about it and didn't attribute any significance to the tarnished piece of metal.<br>
 &quot;You told me you had it.&quot;  Was the careful response.  Immediately Millikin's eyes narrowed in suspicion.<br>
 &quot;No.  I know you didn't find out from me as I am very certain I didn't tell anyone I had it.&quot;  <br>
 &quot;Then Dermonar did.&quot;  Valdayana stated dismissively.  &quot;You can meet up with me and hand it over this evening.&quot;  <br>
Millikin's mood was rapidly deteriorating.  Her response to the enchanter was less than cordial and laced with sarcasm. <br>
 &quot;Thank you so much for planning my evening for me, without even consulting me, first, dear.&quot;  <br>
 &quot;You're quite welcome.&quot;  Valdayana was either oblivious to or chose to ignore the ranger's flippancy.  'Probably the latter.'  Millikin thought which irritated her even more.  <br>
 &quot;I'm in the middle of Hell Frozen Over right now, so meeting tonight is unlikely.  I also don't have the medallion piece on me.  It's hidden in a cache somewhere.&quot;<br>
 &quot;Then fetch it.&quot;  That was the final response from the enchanter before the mental communique ended.<br>
<br>
 'Just who in the Nine Hells does she think she is?'  As the ranger's temper was about to boil over, another thought occurred to her.  'What is so special about that medallion piece?'  In spite of the fact that Valdayana's patronizing manner had the extreme effect of either amusing or (as in this instance) irritating the ranger,  (After all, you can only excuse venerable age so much from someone who often talks down to you before your own patience runs out.  And while patience was generally considered a mandatory trait of a long lived race, compared to most older elves of all subraces, dwarves, and halflings, Millikin had yet to refine it.) Millikin would have cheerfully handed over the medallion to Valdayana without another question except one thing...<br>
<br>
She lied about how she knew the ranger had it. (Millikin figured that the enchanter really used some form of divination magic to ascertain who had the medallion piece.  Not unbelievable in her mind since the Valdayana eerily knew things about her that no one else did and seemed to delight in unnerving the younger ranger with that fact on occasion.)  An obvious conclusion was that she didn't want her to know it's real value.  And the manner by which the luhtmauyar asked, indicated she wanted the ranger to think she was doing her a favor.  In all, Valdayana's high handed command, which was her usual effective tactic of browbeating compliance from others, only served to trigger a streak of contrariness in Millikin.  <br>
<br>
Later that evening, she fished the medal out of a box she had hidden away and studied it closely.  The markings thereon meant nothing to her so she decided to show it to someone she could trust who might be able to provide her with more information about the medal.<br>
