<br>
  Travel did not bear the same time consuming meaning with the Minstrel as it did most.  Her abilities under the compositions of the bard Selo graced her with movement that merely left a trail of stunned onlookers in her wake.  And so upon the simple summons of the ranger, Autumn designated their place of meeting to be Qeynos.  Upon her arrival in the plains of Karana she withdrew her small travel drums of stretched walrus skin and wood from her packs and cradled it snugly under one arm.  A baleful glance was cast upward as the clouds threatened rain and she determined Karana needed a new hobby since she felt like a mushroom each time she traveled through his domain.  She picked up the beat on her drums and swiftly the music wrapped around her, covering her in a mist and raising her feet from the ground.  With the echo of bongos in her wake she took off with a speed unknown to most.<br>
<br>
 Her arrival in the city was swift, and the welcome of the guards of Antonious Bayle were warm as always.  Her eye did not miss the occasional glower however and she met their gaze with equal resolve, and placed a threatening hand upon the hilt of crystalline blade at her hip.  It was enough to make the guard keep walking.  The politics, intrigue and very corrupt nature of half of the city was nearly as bad as Freeport at times.  As Autumn had dabbled in the Freeport quagmire, she also had here, always with some measure of cost.<br>
<br>
 Weaving through the narrow paths and allies a hand reached up to pluck one of the pink flora that grew upon the wall ivy and she tucked it neatly behind one ear as she set foot in the South district of the city.  She spotted Millikin at once, sitting across from the clock at the well in the heart of town.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Hail Millikin!  What is this you have me running half way across the world to discuss?&quot;  The bard quipped with a smile, as both she and Millikin knew that the run Autumn boasted of was hardly that.<br>
<br>
 She took a seat beside the ranger at the well, stretching her legs a moment to recover from her run.  Her face betrayed her curiosity as she watched Millikin withdraw a small wrapped item from her pack and then slipped it in the hands of the bard.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I had hoped you could divine something of the meaning behind this.&quot;  The ranger shrugged before recounting a brief history.  &quot;Dermonar and I battled the skeleton that roams near Firiona Vie.  I discovered this on its remains before we continued on our way.&quot;<br>
<br>
 Pushing aside the cloth that protected it, Autumn studied the piece a moment.  It was indeed from the lands of Kunark, and while the bard could not decipher the writings, they were also not unfamiliar to her from the time she spent questing the coins for the tambourine of Nostrolo.  She admittedly could not read all of those coins without the aid of song either.  Exhaling softly she then drew in a long breath from parted lips before an almost eerie melody pervaded her lips.  From the music a soft golden glow sparkled around the bards eyes momentarily and as she surveyed the piece the golden shimmer seemed to move across it in a flash.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Hmm.&quot;  Autumn squinted at the piece a moment more before looking up at Millikin.  &quot;A unique piece here Mill.  I sense many hands upon it.  The writing is old, one of the original Iksar tribes.  It bears some holy significance to them.  Since they are of a primitive culture I would assume it derives from a shamanic nature.  I also sense the wrath of Sathir upon it as well as the seeking eye of an emperor long lost.&quot;  She paused letting her words sink in a moment before tacking on a touch more information.  &quot;I would seek the spirit of Emperor Ganak... he is still within this world... and I gather he is really looking for this.&quot;  <br>
<br>
 As soon as the words were done the luster of the song was gone, the window of information abruptly shut before the bards eyes.  Shaking off the effects of the song she wrapped the piece once more and pressed it into the hands of the ranger.  &quot;Seek Ganek my friend, as I doubt Sathir would grant you an audience.  He is too busy toying around in that undead infested worm hole of a castle that smells like wet dog.&quot;  She grinned at her last comment which also brought forth a smile from her companion.  <br>
