Skyshrine.<br>
<br>
     The dark furred timber wolf padded beyond the golem sentries and guardian drakes found on the first floor of the fortress that served as home to the friends of the Dragonkin and the lair of Lord Yelinak, leader of the Claws of Veeshan.  Unretractable claws clicked in a rhythmic pace as the wolf wandered the labyrinth passages and up the large winding marble stairs and across the stone floors.  Occasionally the wolf would blink out of sight whenever she stepped on a marked panel designed to translocate a traveler to another section of Skyshrine.  Finally the wolf arrived at her intended location within Skyshrine.  She reached up to push open the door with both forepaws enabling her to slip through the door in a blur of motion before it closed behind her.  The wolf deliberately sniffed the air and nodded slightly.  'She was here.'  She then stalked silently across the carpeted floor towards the one she sought.<br>
<br>
     The Teir`Dal enchanter was sitting at a table, engrossed in reading a book of some sort and didn't seem to indicate she noticed the door of the library open.  Grinning wolfishly, she dropped down low to the floor and silently crept over to the table. The enchanter gave no indication of awareness to anything beyond the contents of the book before her; despite the fact a wolf was stalking her.  Suddenly the wolf sprang upwards putting both forepaws on the table beside the Teir`Dal.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Hi.&quot;  The wolf did not actually speak verbally but employed a form of spirit speech, audible only to those for whom it addressed or whom the speaker willed in proximity to hear.  The Teir`Dal never looked up from her book.  She knew perfectly well who it was (And it was no one who warranted her undivided attention at this time.) and her only response to the greeting was an expert poke in the wolf's ribs.<br>
  &quot;Oww.&quot;  The wolf, or Millikin Erreene as friends and associates knew her, recoiled from the jab and dropped to the floor.  That one hurt more than normal and she glowered up at the enchanter when an idea seized her.  She had watched the spellcaster often enough in the Halls of Testing to know where she kept the material components for her favored protective spell and before the enchanter could react, the timber wolf had snagged the pouch holding several tiny periodots and gulped it down.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You will make yourself ill eating so many of those.&quot;  The warning was not spoken out of actual concern for the ranger's physical health.  Personally Valdayana D`Varr wouldn't have cared one iota if the ranger died in some alleyway somewhere vomiting up all of her internal organs in the street, but periodots were a rather costly gem to purchase from jewelers.<br>
  &quot;It's worth it.  Since you won't be able to recast your rune spell.&quot;  Millikin replied triumphantly.  Valdayana looked up from her book to watch in mild amusement as the wolf finished swallowing her component pouch.  She still had several periodots kept in her pants pocket in case she needed them, in the off chance a skilled pickpocket (Or aggrieved ranger in this case.) managed to pilfer her regular supply.  There was no need to tell her that though.  Especially since the foolish girl may take a notion in her head to try and eat those next.  And entertaining as the idea was, she did not feel inclined to wasting her magical energies on the ranger this day to teach her proper respect for her power.  Particularly while she still had plenty of other equally amusing ways to torment the ranger.<br>
<br>
     She looked back down at her book and poked the lupine ranger in the side once more, knowing perfectly well it would annoy her.  Sure enough, the wolf started gnawing on her hand in an effort to bite her finger off.  The attempts at actually sinking her teeth into flesh were frustrated by the protective barrier designed to block physical and many forms of magical damage to the enchanter.  Valdayana rested her chin on her free hand and watched dispassionately.  Most times, it only took a few bites until Millikin would desist, realizing the rune spell was not going dissipate anytime soon.  Other times, like this one, when the wood elf's mood was more... feral, she would continually try to wear down the rune shield in hopes of breaking through.  Until Valdayana shoved her finger further down the wolf's throat to trigger an involuntary gag reflex so she could disengage her hand during the inevitable choking fit.  <br>
<br>
<br>
     For her own part, Millikin shook her head as her eyes watered from the gag spasm, and mentally counted to ten.  She was forgetting the reason she was here.  The first thing she saw as her vision cleared was Valdayana's smug expression and it gave Millikin pause.  Maybe she should trust her instincts and refuse.  But the ranger's own personal code of honor dictated that she repay a favor if she could, even though it came to her as a demand.  That same sense of obligation did not extend however to allowing someone with evil intentions to further foul agendas.  She was willing to give Valdayana D`Varr the benefit of the doubt.<br>
<br>
  &quot;What are you looking for in Veeshan's Peak?&quot;  Millikin stared over at the enchanter and waited for an answer.<br>
So, she figured out what the medallion was for, did she?  No matter.  She probably doesn't know much else.<br>
  &quot;I like dragons.  And they like me too.  Surely you know that?&quot;  The enchanter replied with artificial seriousness as she closed the book before her on the table and stood up.  It was a deliberate maneuver to make the wolfish ranger dispel her wolf form or look up at her.<br>
  &quot;The Ring of Scale has differing views than the Claws of Veeshan.&quot;  Millikin was not ignorant of the split between the dragons that led to the formation of the Ring of Scale.  Nor was she going to follow Valdayana's lead in the mental dance.  She climbed into another chair nearby and sat down.<br>
  &quot;The Ring of Scale likes me also.  I wish to learn from them.&quot;  Valdayana stated.<br>
  &quot;And how did you manage that?  By slaying your own kind or bards?&quot;  Millikin scoffed.<br>
  &quot;If you must know, I spent time lurking in Mistmoore, helping to thwart Mayong's plans to become immortal.  And steal his knowledge.&quot;  The enchanter volunteered with skillfully staged reluctance.  It was no secret to her that Millikin harbored a hatred of the vampire lord and his minions, mostly Teir`Dal, that claimed dominion of a sizeable realm near her homeland and decided to play on that.<br>
<br>
      Instantly Millikin's thoughts shifted to the Avenging Caitiff she had met in Mistmoore.  A caitiff was an individual who pursued the path of vampiric immortality but were eventually cast out by the vampire master as unacceptable, usually before being turned but after acquiring a measure of unholy power.  Why they were not destroyed vary in reason from each individual.  Some escaped final death, others who had simply fallen out of favor with their master and must regain it.  Others became a caitiff because they (Like the one she had met.) seek vengeance on a vampire.  <br>
  &quot;I see.&quot;  Millikin's eyes narrowed darkly.  Was Valdayana a caitiff?  She sniffed cautiously, knowing those marked as Mayong's Agents by scent or glyph if she looked for it.  An aura of poisonous death clung to them that could not be casually concealed even if they abandoned him.<br>
  &quot;What?&quot;  Valdayana looked at her with practiced innocence.<br>
  &quot;Do you seek immortality?  Or a way to extend your lifespan beyond what is natural?&quot;  Millikin replied to the question with another question of her own.<br>
  &quot;Not anymore.&quot;  Valdayana replied slyly.<br>
  &quot;Then what are you looking for among the dragonkin?&quot;  <br>
  &quot;I can't tell you everything.&quot;  She poked the ranger once more.<br>
  &quot;If you want something from me, I want to know why and what for.  I can't simply hand it over if it's going to be used for some nefarious purpose.&quot;  Millikin stared at her once again.<br>
  &quot;Such is your choice.  It's probably wise considering my history.&quot;  Valdayana stated dismissively.  &quot;But I told you I wish to learn more from the dragons.&quot;<br>
  &quot;If not immortality, then what object or device of power are you seeking?&quot;<br>
  &quot;Knowledge.  I understand you cannot comprehend that though.&quot;  Valdayana crossed her arms in front of her and took her usual tone of condescension with the ranger.<br>
  &quot;You do not seek knowledge for its own sake.  Even I am not that naïve as to believe such of you.&quot;  <br>
  &quot;If you've already come to your own conclusions then why do you have to question me?  You obviously know it all, right?&quot;  <br>
  &quot;I'm not arrogant enough to claim to know everything.  That's your venue.  What makes you think I've come to any conclusion?&quot;  Instantly Millikin became defensive.<br>
  &quot;You are dismissing what I say as I say it.&quot;  Valdayana poked Millikin once again before sitting in her chair once again.                <br>
  &quot;You are dancing around the question.&quot;  She snapped at Valdayana's hand, deliberately missing it.<br>
  &quot;Am not.&quot;  The enchanter reopened her book.  Her response was in lilting singsong mockery to Millikin's statement.      <br>
  &quot;Stop playing games with me.&quot;  Millikin snarled angrily.  Valdayana looked up from her book and fixed a contemplatively appraising look at the wolf sitting across from her.  <br>
  &quot;No.&quot;  She stated flatly and resumed reading her book.<br>
<br>
     Millikin stared in disbelief.  How had the conversation turned around like this?  She dropped down from her chair and moved closer to the enchanter.  What was that book?  Maybe it would be more informative as to the luhtmauyar's intentions.  In the blink of an eye, she transformed back into a wood elf.  Valdayana ignored her and Millikin looked down at the pages.  She couldn't quite make out the words as the letters kept crawling around the pages like bugs.  As she tried to follow their movements, she suddenly staggered back stunned momentarily.  Valdayana smiled to herself as the warding seal placed on the book to prevent unauthorized perusal of its contents took effect. <br>
  &quot;What specific knowledge are you looking for then?&quot;  Millikin persisted in her questioning.<br>
  &quot;I hear they make a mean Mountain Giant stew.&quot;  Valdayana quipped, turning the page of her book once more.<br>
  &quot;Maybe I should rephrase.  By what reason should I hand over the medallion piece to you?&quot;  Millikin sighed.  <br>
Valdayana had to give her credit for determination in trying to ascertain her business in Veeshan's Peak.<br>
  &quot;You should let me have it because it's the right thing to do, of course.&quot;  Valdayana poked her in the arm.  &quot;Because I've done so much for you.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Like what?&quot;  Millikin looked at her skeptically.  The ranger was most curious to hear Valdayana's observations on such matters.<br>
  &quot;I've made you an accepted and tolerated member of the community.  You were an outcast dark ranger before, but I brought you back.&quot;  Valdayana stated sagely.<br>
     Millikin blinked several times then laughed openly at such a ridiculous statement.<br>
  &quot;Accepted by whom?  And more important what community?  That's not necessarily a good thing.  And since when was I ever considered important, particularly to you?&quot; <br>
  &quot;Oh you're not, I'm just trying to make you feel better.&quot;  Valdayana replied.<br>
  &quot;I feel fine.  You are the one obviously in a delusional state.  Look, Valdayana  I&quot;  Millikin was about to explain exactly why she had misgivings about handing of the medallion piece to her.  No response was forthcoming and the ranger paused and looked at the dark elf spellcaster still reading.  Why should she waste her time explaining the concepts of her own personal honor to someone who would doubtless make a mockery of them as surely as she had done so to her just now?  Millikin's eyes narrowed in resolve at her decision. <br>
<br>
     Millikin Erreene would not willingly give Valdayana D`Varr her medallion piece without being convinced it would not be used for a sinister objective.  The ranger abruptly turned on her heel and departed the Skyshrine librarium without another word.<br>
