<p align=right>When I set out to lead humanity along my Golden Path I promised a lesson<br>
their bones would remember. I know a profound pattern humans deny with<br>
words even while their actions affirm it. They say they seek security and<br>
quiet, conditions they call peace. Even as they speak, they create seeds of<br>
turmoil around them.<br>
--The God Emperor from <i>Chapterhouse Dune</i></p><br>
<br>
“Do you know what you’re doing?”<br>
<br>
Esmalyn secured a runaway lock with her upswept ear. <i>If she asks one more time...</i><br>
<br>
Niedre stood in the hallway, arms crossed under her chest. She was surprised to learn this assignment required the skills of a <i>shebale.</i> In a flash of hand signals Esmalyn insisted she check the wing upon entry. There was no time to argue. Leaving Niedre to nurse personal doubts, Esmalyn returned half an hour later and led them to the chamber.<br>
<br>
She glanced askance at Esmalyn. Disheveled hair, hood thrown back. A bandoleer housing balanced daggers crossed her left shoulder and came down at an angle, buckled around the right thigh. There was a softness about her face not common to Tier’Dal, but the scar across the eye surely diverted attention to it. As far as habits were concerned, rumors about her reluctance to work with others were right on target.<br>
 <br>
A warm air current brushed Niedre's cheek. She snapped out of her daze and faced the direction. The fidgeting nature of her movements was not lost to Esmalyn. “What is it?” she asked offhandedly.<br>
<br>
"I saw... Nothing.” <br>
<br>
Esmalyn moved her hands away from the opaline coffin and sat in silence.<br>
<br>
“Although long exposure to strong odors such as the bodies of slaves, incense, and mold will erode your sense of smell over time, you will learn to stretch the limits of other awareness. You were not born with extended ears simply to clip exploits onto them for bragging rights!”<br>
<br>
<i>Oh shut up, Hekzin. Why am I thinking of you now?</i><br>
<br>
Twenty meters ahead a stagnant pool supplied by a stalactite, the sound of dripping water amplified by the hollow, dark metal that formed the Tower of Frozen Shadows. Somewhere to the left the groaning of rotted wood. After a minute, she picked up the needle-thin knife and shim and slid them between the lid and casket. Inching slowly, deliberately, she came full circle. No surface defects, no triggers.<br>
<br>
She exhaled. “I need your hands.”<br>
<br>
Niedre entered the dome-shaped burial chamber. They faced each other across the dead. She was tall for a dark elf, one hand taller than Esmalyn. And vain.<br>
<br>
<i>Unwilling to crop that brazen long hair. How impractical in our present surroundings.</i> They reached down for the lid. Esmalyn caught a glimpse of cobwebs clinging to the fanned bottom. <i>She won’t even stoop to a braid.</i> <br>
<br>
”On three.”<br>
<br>
<i>Worst of all, she’s with the Mask.</i><br>
<br>
”One...two...” Esmalyn nodded once.<br>
<br>
The lid came free with an unnatural swoosh of air, chased by the crackle of eldritch magic. Neither of them moved. An amusing idea struck Esmalyn in spite of herself then: <i>This is why we reserve the right to charge so high a tariff.</i><br>
<br>
From the hallway blared a female voice, laughing, cajoling; ranging from a resonant child to the tear-streaked heaves of an old woman and ended with the wail of battered swine--each delivery pitched to freeze the marrow in bones. The transparent hair on the backs of both rogues’ neck rose to the occasion.<br>
<br>
<i>Tserrina.</i><br>
<br>
A knot twisted in Niedre's throat. The initial stun and the realization that she may not live passed, had been accepted. She spat, "Why didn’t you check for dweomers!”<br>
<br>
Esmalyn, canting her head to the side, asked, “Did you take care not to step on a sigil?”<br>
<br>
Niedre looked down. A marker illuminated the heal of her right boot in green light. Her eyes shot up to Esmalyn's. <i>Anger in those eyes,</i> Niedre thought. <i>She means to kill me if we live.</i> <br>
<br>
The wheezing from the hallway eventually faded. Their arms trembled from the extended hold. Of one accord Niedre and Esmalyn discarded the lid just as they put the pretense of stealth behind them. The lid cracked in half against the raised effigy of a dark knight, hairline cracks spread from the center.<br>
<br>
There lay an Erudite male in the coffin, the claymore in his hands extended beyond his feet. It had a demystifying effect on the riddle of the long, opaline coffin. Esmalyn almost sighed. He was dressed in velvet finery down to gold-dipped gloves.<br>
<br>
“You see?” Niedre pointed into the coffin. “The Gashrek Scrolls do not lie!”<br>
<br>
Esmalyn seized Niedre’s wrist away from the circlet and yelled: “The dance is just beginning!” It was the first time she raised her voice above a whisper since crawling through one of the chutes concealed by the talon-like buttresses outside.<br>
<br>
Niedre jerked her arm back. The source of Esmalyn’s agitation began in the hallway once more. Except it was not ethereal, but the real clash of metal striking stone, running inexorably towards them.<br>
<br>
Niedre reached for the circlet again. The skeleton’s neck snapped at the base and, taking a sword in her left hand, she shook the skull free. It bounced down the hallway and spun on its crown a few times before a giant boot crushed it.<br>
<br>
Arming her dagger, Niedre backed away until she hit the wall. Likewise armed, Esmalyn positioned herself behind the casket. She quipped, “How does one kill armor?”<br>
<br>
That decided the armor’s first target. Minus well take the brunt of it now, she thought. The...thing ducked into the chamber. Its helmet ground against the entry and loosened a piece of stone. Once inside, it turned a glowing-white stare on Esmalyn. A closed fist swooped at her. Easily dodged, but as it flew overhead the hum of air in its passing was a testament to the power behind it.<br>
<br>
Niedre crept forward on her toes. Normally inclined to open an assault with her dagger, she opted for the sword’s longer reach. It drew a line of sparks across the armor’s breastplate. The armor whirled on her, a fist striking down.<br>
<br>
<i>She cannot hope to stop it!</i><br>
<br>
Niedre caught the gauntlet by the handle of her sword. She nearly fell on her knees from the force, and her balance tipped. The other gauntlet caught her swordhand in an iron grip, squeezed until bones snapped by the numbers. The sword fell from the crushed fingers.<br>
<br>
Esmalyn had no intentions of dragging dead weight around, but the circlet still sat on that inbred's brow. She thrust dagger and sword into their sheaths with a <i>snick.</i> Hoisting a shield from the effigies nearly as long as her and twice as wide she slid a wrist through the handle and bashed the armor. The effort did little more than annoy it, but at least it turned around. Esmalyn saw Niedre hobble out of sight, the expression on her face full of spite. <br>
<br>
It was Esmalyn's turn to get tossed around like a rag doll. By chance she ended up under the shield. The pounding wouldn't relent, and it would not be long before the shield gave out. She would scream, but to what avail? Niedre would likely not return even if uninjured. In all probability, she was cutting the rope right now.<br>
<br>
Esmalyn promised herself not to return without good cause. <i>No, better cause. And alone.</i> She timed the next punch and scrambled out when the gauntlet reached its zenith. Her hand produced a tiny dagger and her wrist flicked for the eyes. It sank deep, breaking the plane of the visor. The armor clawed at it, moaned, and pushed the coffin over in a fit of rage.<br>
<br>
She leapt to her feet and abandoned the room, the treasures inside suddenly unimportant. She found Niedre at the chute's mouth, the rope cradled in her injured arm while her good hand cut.<br>
<br>
"I wouldn't do that," Esmalyn warned.<br>
<br>
”I should have never agreed!"<br>
<br>
<i>She sounds so petty.</i><br>
<br>
Esmalyn turned around. "Who's there?"<br>
<br>
"What?" It was Niedre. "How could they even consider you?" Accusing.<br>
<br>
Esmalyn looked up, eyes narrowed. "You spoiled <i>elg'caress.</i> Don't blame your incompetence on me."<br>
<br>
<i>That's the spirit!</i><br>
<br>
<i>I am going mad,</i> she thought.<br>
<br>
<i>Not quite. We are simply sharing a link.</i><br>
<br>
<i>Who is this?</i><br>
<br>
<i>Valdayana, none other. You'd better take action. Your friend is coming soon.</i><br>
<br>
Esmalyn blinked.<br>
<br>
<i>Pleasantly surprised, I take it.</i><br>
<br>
<i>I'm not a damned telepath. Neither do I remember inviting you into my mind.</i><br>
<br>
<i>D on't carp with me! Get the circlet.</i> The last word was accompanied by a mental jab.<br>
<br>
Esmalyn took a step back. Gathering herself, she unsheathed the dagger, turned Niedre around by the arm and drew a clean line across her throat. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/uesmalyn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Esmalyn</A> at: 1/15/02 10:16:52 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/uesmalyn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Esmalyn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Bitch Queen</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(1/15/02 10:19:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fragments - The Frayed Ends (Part II)</span><hr size=1> <h4>© 2002 L.H.</h4><br>
Valdayana. The pretentious enchanter stricken with delusions of godhood. Not that it made a difference to Esmalyn. The closest she came to accepting a credo was a brush with the clergy of Luclin. But since then their fundamental belief had shifted, a signal that the goddess had as well.<br>
<br>
She sat in the corner of the dragonspire, waiting for a wizard to chance by. During the exchange she polished the circlet to its former luster then wiped the soot off her face. She could still taste the grit in her mouth from the chamber floor and periodically leaned over to spit. She also took care not to conceal her opinion of the enchanter during the conversation.<br>
<br>
<I>Wipe that grin off your face.<br>
<br>
Does it offend you?<br>
<br>
You are not worth my consideration.<br>
<br>
Obviously.</I> Sarcasm. Esmalyn wrapped the circlet in a cloth and tucked it underneath her tunic.<br>
<br>
<I>The arrangement has been made. Will you accept the terms?<br>
<br>
What of the ranger?</I><br>
<br>
A pause. <I>She is resourceful. She may be of use yet.</I><br>
<br>
The rogue felt the other's influence diminish. <br>
<br>
Esmalyn stepped away from the spires of Shadowhaven holding her gut. Travel by magical means wasn’t kind. She leaned over the waters and washed her hands and face while her innards anchored themselves to the lighter gravity on the moon. It was possible Millikin was away from the city on one of her many excursions. And highly likely that her quarters was clear of theft deterrents, mundane or otherwise.<br>
<br>
<I>Reasons why the witch asked for me.</I><br>
<br>
She did not break into the flat. She didn't ask after the target. Esmalyn browsed the merchant tents outside and replaced some items, but always with an eye on the corner door on the second floor. No telling what setting Millikin's inner clock had adjusted to without the sun to guide her hours.<br>
<br>
It was an hour before she approached the flat. The lock was fashioned after a popular design. She turned the doorknob and entered on the ‘click,’ shutting the door behind her. Waiting a moment for her eyes to adjust to the darkness, she took in her surroundings.<br>
<br>
A small flat with a single room. There were provisions for cooking and washing, the furnishings sparse and simplistic. In the rear and under a window Millikin rested on her back, eyes occasionally blinking in the meditative state of reverie.<br>
<br>
It wasn't long before Esmalyn found the medallion in a satchel. <I>How very trusting,</I> she thought. She rolled it between her fingers as she went over the conversation with Valdayana.<br>
<br>
<I>She did not only want to keep her alive, but ignorant of the folly for as long as possible.</I><br>
<br>
Esmalyn kicked the railing at Millikin's feet so hard the pegs shunted.<br>
<br>
<I>I spin my own chaos.</I><br>
<br>
Millikin sat bolt upright, shaking the reverie off. Her hand intrinsically reached for Swiftwind.<br>
<br>
<I>Ironic. We serve Innoruuk from time to time, whether or not we swoon to the sermon.</I><br>
<br>
Esmalyn waited for recognition on the ranger’s face.<br>
<br>
"You?" she asked.<br>
<br>
The rogue raised the medallion by the string. "Regards from your friend."<br>
<br>
Recognition changed into betrayal. Millikin tried to run Esmalyn through. Swiftwind struck the gaseous vapors of gate spells.<br>
<br>
A bottle crashed on the floor. Before the outline completely faded a distant voice whispered, "You should thank me." <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/uesmalyn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Esmalyn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Bitch Queen</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(1/15/02 10:20:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fragments - The Frayed Ends (OOC Notes)</span><hr size=1> Posted with the permission of all involved.<br>
