<br>
Shadow Haven<br>
<br>
Millikin crumpled into a chair after her latest spate of vomiting.  A handful of blood flecked pale green stones were scattered on a table in front of her alongside the majority of her equipment.  The last thing the ranger expected she would be doing this evening was dry heaving periodots at a secluded inn in the Fordel District in Shadow Haven.  The elf leaned back in the chair and stared up at the ceiling.  She had been warned that eating them would make her sick.  At the time it seemed to be a worthwhile consideration. Hindsight, as always, proved to be 20/20 though and she mused that eating Valdayana’s supply of periodots was not the most effective and worthwhile means of dealing with her.  While Millikin didn’t begrudge the fact that she was paying the price for eating those gems in her wolf form, it did irk her that Valdayana was right about the end result.  She looked out the window of her rented room from old habit.  Neither the stars nor the moon was visible, and only served to remind her that technically she was in a subterranean series of caves and tunnels on the moon of Luclin.  ‘Why did she always have to be right?  And furthermore how did she always manage to get the upper hand in any dealings with her?’  Millikin slumped forward in her chair and closed her eyes.   <br>
<br>
Well, not entirely this time.  Millikin had something the enchanter wanted.  And she wasn’t going to get it with her current attitude.  A while back, Millikin had acquired a medallion section that Valdayana currently needed.  The piece itself was worthless to her but was a means to acquiring something of more immediate worth to her.  After going through a somewhat tangled skein to unravel what, Millikin learned that the enchanter was looking for entrance to Veeshan’s Peak, a sealed sanctuary for another sect of dragons and dragonkin called the Ring of Scale.  The Tunarean ranger would not be a willing party to any plot the Teir`Dal was scheming to undermine the interests of her goddess or further the objectives of whichever dark power the spellcaster had aligned herself with to increase her own personal powerbase.  When she questioned Valdayana as to her purpose to going to Veeshan’s Peak, the enchanter manipulated the direction of the conversation with off-the-wall statements, appeals to what the ranger owed her, and even placed Millikin on the defensive for questioning her motives in the first place.  The ranger eventually left in frustration, knowing nothing more as to the enchanter’s intentions as before she went to ask her, except that she was not going to give her the medallion piece as originally intended until she was sure its use would not be for some sinister means.  Feverishly she sat up and poured herself a glass of water from the pitcher on the table and swallowed it down, hoping she would not resume vomiting.  After a few moments she staggered over to the bed and wearily reached for the blanket lying at the foot of the bed.<br>
<br>
As a rule, Millikin was not one to question the concept of deific intervention in the lives of mortals.  Though she did tend to view that the objectives were ultimately for good or ill depending on the god involved and that sentient beings would (and should) react according to their nature but everything that happens is for some larger purpose.  As such, she did wonder at this very moment what possible reason Tunare could have for Millikin to be acquainted with an enchanter who would slander the goddess and denigrate her chosen servants.  The only thing she could think of was that Valdayana D`Varr was an example of how Millikin should NOT behave.  The ranger kicked her blanket aside as she mentally replayed the conversation in Skyshrine once again.  This time, mostly angry at herself that she allowed herself to be so utterly led astray from the topic at hand.  ‘Dark ranger.  Trust such a concept to come from a Teir`Dal.’  As the wood elf ranger fell into a disturbed state of reverie the talisman she always wore around her neck flickered briefly.  <br>
<br>
From the Demi-Plane of Nightmares, Terris Thule watched the world of Norrath, ever vigilant to find those who could satiate her desire.  Like many of the deities of Norrath, she drew sustenance from mortals.  For some it was not enough to have their worship, they required more from their devout and either fed off their emotions or the ones their followers engendered in others.  Whether or not such consumption of emotional energy actually strengthened the deity or simply a habitual facet of their persona to demand of their worshippers was unknown and certainly a subject of debate amongst religious leaders.  But what was a known fact is that Dream Scorcher sought the mental distress of those who experienced nightmares and a preferential taste for the nightmares of the innocent and good.  Whenever possible, she drew the spirits of such people into her realm for consumption.  In such a case, one could only remain in her realm for as long as their bodies physically slept, thus Terris Thule would expand one’s nightmares to astounding realism to convince her victim they were not dreaming and she could continue to feed from their fears and uncertainties.  Since Terris Thule’s power was not infinite, she selected her prey carefully to ensure she could keep them in her custody for as long as possible.  Those prone to fear would awaken themselves in a fit of terror or would be light sleepers where the slightest distraction from the material world would draw them from her clutches.  Those who were extremely strong willed tend to realize where they were and shatter the illusions of her nightmare world with their departure.  Therefore Terris Thule tended to steal away those who were both mentally and physically weary.<br>
<br>
Falling…<br>
<br>
‘Somehow… this isn’t my place.’  Millikin thought to herself<br>
‘Of course not.  You’ve been spirit shifted.’  The spirit wolf replied.<br>
‘To where?’  Millikin looked around.  Everything seemed to be a fugue.<br>
<br>
Falling…<br>
<br>
‘I do not know yet.  Allow me the control.’  The spirit wolf spoke into her mind once more.  <br>
<br>
Falling…<br>
<br>
‘I am more experienced in traversing different realms in this manner.  You cannot even find your way out of the Shadow Realms.  The spirit sensed the ranger’s hesitation.  ‘I will get us back to our own realm.’  In a second’s time the wolf spirit subsumed the elf’s.<br>
<br>
Falling… <br>
<br>
The lift stopped moving and without a word, Millikin Erreene stomped past Guard Pineshade.  The Kelethin guard watched her go with barely a nod in greeting.  The ranger’s reputation for mercurial mood swings was as well known as her reputation for ruthless efficiency.  Dressed in dark leathers and wielding serrated short blades, she made her way towards the Butcherblock Mountains.  A flash of eldritch light off to her right briefly caught her attention.  She turned to see a high elf wizard casting a fire based spell.  Millikin’s eyes narrowed when she saw the wizard’s target - a black wolf.  The wolf yelped in pain then leapt at its attacker.   Apparently this wizard was a novice to the Art because she was unable to cast another spell as the wolf continued to claw and bite her.  The wizard desperately turned to run towards the gates of Felwithe, when Millikin started to recite an incantation.  Grass and weeds shot up to wrap around the wizard’s ankles, slowing her flight to safety considerably.  The wizard watched horrorstruck as the wolf lunged for her throat and dragged her to the ground.  A twisted grin appeared on Millikin’s face as the wolf continued to maul the unconscious elf for several more moments before trotting off.  &quot;Next time stay behind the safety of your marble walls, Koada`Dal.&quot;  The ranger remarked coldly as she continued.<br>
<br>
Millikin was, once again, being sent on messenger errands to and from Kelethin, Kithicor, and Highpass Hold.  Acting as courier between the master rangers patrolling Kithicor and Faydark's Champions to keep tabs on the Teir`Dal activity in the area.  Initially she had been surprised to learn that a dark elf stronghold existed within Kithicor and that numerous dark elf agents ran between Highpass Hold and Neriak.  Surprise quickly turned to contempt when she also discovered that the orcs of Clan Schralok were permitted to live near the mountain pass to Highhold Keep.  Then at night the forests were overrun with undead.  <br>
<br>
‘These humans are useless.’ she concluded.  They could have easily called upon assistance from Freeport or even Qeynos to eradicate the Schralok orcs who hunted the tigers and wolves that once populated Kithicor forest to nigh extinction and then further worked to drive out the Teir`Dal from the forests.  She was fairly sure that even King Tearis Thex would have dispatched a contingent of troops to assist in that endeavor.  <br>
<br>
One day as she prowled Kithicor’s forests she ducked into the tunnel entrance leading to the halfling’s village to avoid the sudden downpour, when idea began to take shape.  ‘Water.’  She would contaminate the orcs’ water supply.  Instantly she thought of poisoning the entirety of Lake Kithicor to take out both the orcs and the dark elves but immediately decided against that.  Such an act would be too time consuming and likely have adverse effects on the animals that still remained relatively untainted by the corruption that permeated the forest.  She would lace their selected watering holes and decide on how to handle the dark elves later.  The ranger quickly decided on strychnine as the poison of choice.  Within a few weeks time, the orc population declined dramatically as many of them suddenly fell ill and died inexplicably.  A month later, the sudden plague that had stricken the orcs in Kithicor and spread to their kinsman in Highpass and on to the Mucktail Gnolls in Highpass caught the attention of the Church of Rodcet Nife.  By the time Millikin returned to Kelethin to report this incident to the guildmasters, several residents of Kithicor and Highpass citizens had fallen ill as well.  They had learned that the water supply had been poisoned.  Rumors persisted that the Teir`Dal were responsible and this was a prelude to another attack on Highhold Keep.<br>
<br>
She quickly resumed her old habits, terrorizing Crushbone orcs and prowling the fringes of Mistmoore Castle, slaying Mayong Mistmoore’s unwary retainers who lingered too long by themselves.  One day, her hunt went badly.  A band of fools had decided to raid Mistmoore castle.  They never made it beyond the main gates before the standard retinue of guards drove them off.  One of Mayong Mistmoore’s vampiric minions opted to oversee the slaughter and caught sight of the ranger hiding in the shadows of the outer wall.  In a blur of motion, she was upon the ranger cursing and clawing.  The last thing Millikin felt was a bone jarring kick…<br>
<br>
… Jumping to her feet, she reached for her sword and had it clear of its sheath before one could blink.<br>
<br>
‘Why was Esmalyn in her room?’  Confusion turned to anger as she saw her medallion dangling from the dark elf’s fingertips.  Without thought, she lunged towards the rogue only to strike air as she disappeared.<br>
<br>
A rage filled howl echoed through the passages of Shadow Haven.  “Valdayana!”<br>
