  &quot;It hasn't hampered me though.  Watch.&quot;  Valdayana employed a bit of prestidigitation (unnoticed by the ranger) and traced another arcane pattern in midair at the ranger, subtlety activating one of the myriad magical items in her possession.  Millikin felt the effects of the previous spell ebb, the effects replaced by a similar weaker spell.  <br>
  &quot;I'm still capable of removing my blessings from you by replacing it with an inferior spell.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Already you're weakening.&quot;  Millikin rocked back and forth from her heels to toes, hands clasped behind her back, grinning.<br>
  &quot;Don't be ridiculous.  I simply forgot where I wrote the incantation for Breeze in my spellbook.  Back when I was rising to power, when trakaraptors still roamed the Commonlands, &quot; Millikin hid a smile at that remark, trust Valdayana to somehow know a comment she made to Autumn in reference to the luhtmauyar's age.  &quot;Breeze didn't exist as a spell.&quot;<br>
<br>
     Suddenly Millikin's vision blurred momentarily.  She shook her head slightly as the dark elf came into focus once again.  If Valdayana noticed the poison's secondary effect taking hold on the ranger she gave no outward indication as she sat down once more.  For her own part, Millikin found it difficult to focus on a singular thought pattern for any great length of time.  She carefully watched Valdayana D'Varr for several moments.  'She's not attacking… She took something.  What?… A friend?  No…  who is she then?  Millikin's thoughts were a jumble when suddenly the Teir`Dal spoke to her.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Why are you disturbing my meditation now?&quot;  <br>
  &quot;Who me?&quot;  Millikin looked at her quizzically.  She didn't say anything in the past several moments.<br>
  &quot;Yes you.  The only ugly ranger around here I can see.&quot;<br>
  &quot;I'm ugly now?&quot;  Millikin's eyes crossed momentarily and she started wavering momentarily then stopped.<br>
  &quot;You don't match, and your ykesha is beyond outdated.&quot;  Valdayana replied with all the authority of a fully sworn officer of the fashion police.  Millikin looked down at herself.  She wore chain armor of various craftsmanship tinted in shades of green, brown, and grey - ideal coloration for one who finds themself at home in the forests.  She looked at her swords at either side, confusion etched on her face.  'A ykesha?   I thought it was a Swiftblade.  Or was it was called Swiftwind… '<br>
<br>
  &quot;That's what this is?&quot;  She studied the Swiftblade of Zek closely for several moments.<br>
  &quot;Now run along.  I have mysteries to comprehend that extend beyond what your meager intellect can fathom.&quot;  Valdayana waved her off.  'Now that sounded interesting.'  Millikin looked over at the dark elf.<br>
  &quot;Like what?&quot;<br>
  &quot;For instance why certain annoying rangers aren't culled by their kindred as children and grow up into adults who make their family wish they had done so.&quot;<br>
    Millikin's eyesight blurred once again.  'Was that an insult?  Maybe it was a comparison of civilization versus savagery.'   <br>
  &quot;Oh that's easy to answer.&quot;  Millikin responded.  &quot;I think.&quot;<br>
  &quot;From your perspective, not mine.&quot;  Valdayana replied loftily.  &quot;I have to judge the reactions of many since my personal actions can impact the world, as you are no doubt aware.&quot;<br>
  Millikin wavered slightly, taking a half-step to keep from stumbling.<br>
  &quot;As I said, its beyond your ken.  Run along now before I forget myself and make your mind more liquid than it already is.&quot;<br>
  'Liquid… slippery like quicksilver…  Why was the name Quicksilver familiar?'  Millikin's thoughts raced.  'Why can't I think straight?  The poison?'<br>
  &quot;Your perspective is irrelevant.  You aren't a ranger.  Or are you?&quot;  Millikin responded, somehow the realization that she was being denigrated started to register with her as the effects of the poison began to wear off.<br>
  &quot;Dark elves can't be rangers.  That should answer your question.&quot;  While the Feir`Dal mulled over that statement, Valdayana discreetly hid her stave and replaced it with a shortsword she had absconded long ago.<br>
  'She's right.  They can't be rangers.'   &quot;Maybe you aren't really a dark elf.&quot;  Millikin countered after a few moments' thought.<br>
  &quot;Maybe not but then if I was a ranger wouldn't I run around with a sword?&quot;  Valdayana suggested.<br>
  &quot;Like the one in your hand?&quot;  Millikin pointed.<br>
  &quot;How did that get there?&quot;  Valdayana quickly put the shortsword away and once again held her Shissar staff in her hand.  &quot;Besides, I wouldn't be caught dead in the chain mail tunics rangers wear.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Well no self-respecting ranger would carry a shield.  Nor would a warrior, now that you mention it.&quot;  Millikin said after a moment's pause.<br>
  &quot;So call me a paladin and be done with it since that's the obvious conclusion.&quot;  The Teir`Dal announced.  Millikin nodded momentarily as she continued.  &quot;I AM devoted and selfless, constantly taking time to listen to you and the other meaningless people around me.&quot;<br>
     That didn't quite seem right.  Millikin shook her head.<br>
  &quot;No, that's not right.  Paladins can't be dark elves… err that is, dark elves can't be paladins.  Who exactly are you again?&quot;  Millikin looked over at her quizzically.<br>
  &quot;Valdayana D`Varr, second-born daughter to the D`Varr family of Neriak.&quot;  She stated grandly.  &quot;You may have heard of us.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Hrm, I don't think so…&quot;  The Feir`Dal ranger shook her head once again, though the dark elf's name was familiar.  'She's a spellcaster obviously.  Her hideously ugly tunic would preclude any other occupation on sheer eccentricity alone if nothing else.  And she was making comments about MY wardrobe?'  Millikin cleared her throat but Valdayana continued.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You may wish to watch your back.&quot;  <br>
  &quot;Why?&quot;  Millikin turned around but saw nothing but the vendor booth behind her.<br>
  &quot;You've failed to take into consideration that while I may be a loving and caring paladin…&quot;  Valdayana quietly snickered to herself then took a more somber mien.  &quot;My sister is more wayward, and has pursued the necromantic arts.&quot; <br>
  &quot;So…&quot;  Millikin looked at Valdayana blankly.<br>
  &quot;If she were to learn that a ranger was trying to attack me, I fear the end result would be that she would acquire a skeleton pet wearing ugly green chain mail.  She isn't bound by the same constraints of morality as I.&quot; <br>
     Millikin rolled her eyes.  The last thing she was worried about was Valdayana's sister.  Necromancer or otherwise. 'What was it this dark elf stole from her again?' <br>
  &quot;If you were really a paladin, why would I attack you and why would you associate with…  She paused momentarily to recall the word.    …a gurthagular?&quot;<br>
  Valdayana glanced at Millikin with an air of superiority.  <br>
  &quot;You'll have to ask yourself that.  I can't read minds.  Well, I choose not to in your case as it's devoid of substance.&quot;  Millikin's eyes narrowed darkly at the insult as Valdayana stood up.  &quot;As to my sister, well the ties of family are binding.  You should know that since your own family opted not to slaughter you even after your display of ill traits.&quot;<br>
  &quot;You know my family?&quot;<br>
  &quot;Knew.  How long has it been since returned to Kelethin?&quot;  Valdayana asked innocently but the statements implication was obvious.  Millikin grinned to herself.  As it just so happened, she had visited her parents and sister earlier that day after learning a new spellcasting technique from one of the hierophants in Kelethin before meeting up with… 'What was her name again?  Saldaria.'  Had Millikin taken the implied threat seriously, the enchanter would have found the ranger's fingers around her neck, ready to snap it like a twig before she could draw another breath.<br>
  &quot;You probably don't even know who I am.  Much less my family.&quot;  <br>
<br>
     Inexplicably the enchanter walked off, trailed by the ranger, to the duelists' arena before she sat down in the stadium seats.  Millikin looked down to the main combat area.  Despite the fact that her thoughts were a jumble, one word stood out in memory as she looked around.<br>
  &quot;Discord.&quot;  She whispered, mostly to herself.<br>
  &quot;You may be brighter than you look.&quot;  Valdayana commented, her eyes half closed.  Millikin turned to her.<br>
  &quot;Why are you here?&quot;<br>
  &quot;For some peace and quiet that is not happening.&quot;<br>
  &quot;I can't remember what exactly I'm angry with you about.&quot;  Millikin closed her eyes, consciously trying to remember the specifics that seemed hidden in a mental fog as the effects of the poison were dissipating.<br>
  &quot;Hmm?  If you were angry with me, why didn't you say so?&quot;<br>
  &quot;I was certain I did.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Speak up next time.  Now what is it?&quot;  Valdayana spoke briskly.<br>
  &quot;You though I can't quite recall what.&quot;  In her mind's eye, the ranger saw a metal shard marked with glyphs.<br>
  &quot;Let me know when you do.  As always I'll be more than happy to help you.&quot;  She looked over at Millikin, studying the elf's appearance, stance, mannerisms, and facial expressions.  Quickly she analyzed them to ascertain the ranger's possible reaction.<br>
  &quot;You stole something from me.  A piece of metal.&quot;  Millikin opened her eyes; her voice's inflection changed from accusation to a more questioning note in the last sentence.<br>
  &quot;I don't engage in petty theft.  I have minions for that.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Same difference.  You're still a thief.&quot;  Millikin replied.  &quot;Now if I could just remember what…&quot;<br>
  &quot;This?&quot;  Valdayana stood up and held out a necklace she had around her neck for the ranger to examine.  Millikin leaned closer to take a look and immediately her eyes widened in recognition at some of the markings visible on the pendant.  Instantly she remembered the battle with the skeleton with Dermonar where she had lured the skeleton around the riverbanks that fed into Ill Omen Lake while the paladin dispatched a drachnid that had approached during the melee.<br>
  &quot;That's it!&quot;  <br>
  &quot;Not quite.&quot;  Valdayana corrected, releasing the necklace to fall back into her clothes.  &quot;You had only a piece.&quot;<br>
  &quot;From the skeleton.&quot;  Millikin nodded.<br>
  &quot;A useless piece of a shattered relic… I had the means to restore it to its glory to help unravel the disappearance of the iksar tribes.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Yes, and you stole a piece from me--&quot;  Millikin paused at the mention of the iksar tribes disappearing.  &quot;I thought they killed themselves off.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Sometimes people get stepped on in the pursuit of knowledge, unfortunate but true.  You've overreacted in your response I believe.&quot;  She shrugged.  &quot;It's your call to make, and I really can't argue but when your friends start dying due to my current inability to protect them, you know who's head the blame will lie on.&quot;<br>
  &quot;What?&quot;  The last statement in particular struck a nerve with the ranger.<br>
  &quot;I'm not going to explain it to you unless you're really as daft as I insinuate.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Why do you care one way or another?&quot;  Millikin was not about to admit that Valdayana's statement caught her unprepared.<br>
  &quot;The question really is, why don't you.&quot;  Valdayana replied.<br>
  &quot;You go through a lot of trouble to display your contempt of the world.  Why do you care about anyone else's welfare.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Perhaps I get angry because I do care?  Valdayana suggested, poking Millikin in the arm as if to physically emphasize the mental jab to the ranger's conscience her statement was.<br>
  &quot;Because you don't care.&quot;  Millikin's eyes narrowed slightly, but the self-doubt at her own actions was evident to the Teir`Dal.  <br>
  &quot;It doesn't really matter what you think though.&quot;  Valdayana poked Millikin once again, noting the ranger's silence.<br>
<br>
(cont.)<br>
