  &quot;Do you follow the Winding Way?&quot;  Millikin asked after a long silence.<br>
  &quot;Define the Winding Way.&quot;  Valdayana poked Millikin.  The ranger reached up to run her hand along the back of her neck trying to think of how to summarize the philosophy she was referring to.<br>
  &quot;Well basically, there's no purpose but to seek enlightenment… &quot;  Millikin started, pointedly ignoring the luhtmauyar's jabs.<br>
  &quot;I'm not that far gone.&quot;  Valdayana poked her again, knowing it would not be long before her prodding would incite the young ranger. <br>
  &quot;It's called the Winding Way because you progress at your own pace, but the general belief is things come around.  Someone you learn from may be someone you teach later in life.  And vice versa.&quot;  <br>
  &quot;I do my own thing.&quot;  Valdayana poked Millikin once again for emphasis, who nodded slowly and bit her bottom lip once as Valdayana continued.  &quot;As I said you can do what you want.  I won't lose my temper, I'm not that kind of person.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Maybe I misjudged you.&quot;  Millikin spoke after a few moments, frowning slightly, mostly at herself, when Valdayana poked her yet again.<br>
  &quot;And quit poking me.  You're getting that stuff on me.&quot;  The wood elf knelt down and began to rummage through her backpack, oblivious to the fact that Valdayana was grinning like the Cheshire cat as she stood over Millikin watching her with skillfully feigned disinterest.<br>
  &quot;Do me a favor please?&quot;  Millikin asked as she found the desired item and she worked to fish it out from beneath the plethora of items stored in her backpack and looked up at the enchanter.<br>
  &quot;Hmm?&quot;  Valdayana's eyebrows rose speculatively as she waited for Millikin to continue.<br>
  &quot;The next time you want something from me, can you dispose of the condescending attitude?&quot;  Finally pulling out the vial, Millikin stood up and held it up to the light to inspect briefly.&quot;<br>
  &quot;You have more poison for me?&quot;  Valdayana grinned at Millikin smugly.<br>
  &quot;This is the antidote.&quot;  Millikin spoke quietly.  <br>
  &quot;Ah, you've come to your senses.&quot;  Valdayana watched as Millikin tentatively offered her the antidote but made no move to take it.  &quot;Are you sure you want me to have that?&quot;  <br>
  Millikin nodded.  &quot;Yes.&quot;  Her fingers closed around the vial slightly but she still held it out.  &quot;Why?&quot;<br>
  &quot;It seems against your usual nature.  If you truly want to give it to me, I'll take it.&quot;  She held her hand out after a few moments.<br>
  &quot;What do you mean?&quot;  Millikin dropped the vial into her hand.<br>
  &quot;You are very hostile to me.  As evidenced by this evening.&quot;  Valdayana answered, poking the ranger.<br>
  &quot;You have a talent for bringing out the worst in me at times.&quot;  Millikin bristled.  &quot;And quit poking me.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Then perhaps you should work on your self-control.&quot;  Valdayana admonished.  Millikin glared at the dark elf but bit her tongue to refrain from responding with an insult.  She couldn't refute the validity of the advice, solicited or not.<br>
   &quot;And what would you have done if someone stole something from you?&quot;  Millikin asked.<br>
  &quot;That wouldn't happen.  I'm not careless.&quot;  Valdayana responded immediately.<br>
  &quot;I'm not careless either.&quot;  Millikin snapped.<br>
  &quot;Believe what you want, that's your right.&quot;  Valdayana slipped the vial into a pouch.<br>
  &quot;You hired someone to break into my room and go through my personal belongings.&quot;  Millikin growled.<br>
  &quot;But I asked first, did I not?&quot;<br>
  &quot;And I refused.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Which demonstrates your hostility towards me.&quot;  Valdayana watched in slight amusement as Millikin trembled in barely controlled rage.  The ranger clenched and unclenched her hands into fists a few times before responding.<br>
  &quot;You've given me ample reason not to trust you.&quot;  <br>
  &quot;You're welcome to believe that, if you wish to be paranoid, that's your right.&quot;  Valdayana spoke calmly.<br>
  &quot;I am NOT paranoid.&quot;  Millikin replied angrily then took a deep breath.  &quot;You did steal from me and bragged about the thief being willing to kill me in my sleep but didn't on your word.  I honestly wonder why.&quot;  <br>
  &quot;To see how you would react.  And better understand and predict the emotions of lesser races.&quot;<br>
  &quot;That's why you provoke me?  As an experiment.&quot;  Millikin's hands twitched once again in anger.<br>
  &quot;Well, &quot;  Valdayana paused thoughtfully at the question.  &quot;That and it's fun.  Really though, you should know by now its not malicious.&quot;  As she sat down once more, she poked Millikin in the side, who seemed suddenly lost in thought.  <br>
<br>
     'Not malicious?'  Millikin weighed the statement.  Which was worse - the pursuit of power or materialism?  While Millikin didn't mourn the loss of the medallion piece overmuch, she was disturbed over another aspect of this entire situation.  The enchanter, in her search for power, violated the ranger's privacy and personal sense of security.  While the act itself was committed by someone Millikin trusted to an extent, (even if she did not share her ethics) it did not change the fact that the act was done because Valdayana wished it so.  One thing about money is that there was never a shortage of people willing to take it when offered.  If not Esmalyn then certainly another would have.  That, of course, begged the question of why the luhtmauyar went to the trouble of hiring someone known to Millikin in the first place.  She found herself thinking of the caustic comments Valdayana made about Millikin's family earlier.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You are no closer to understanding me now than the day you first met me.  I do wonder though...&quot;  Millikin's hands burned and she found herself shoving them into her pockets.<br>
  &quot;Wonder what?&quot;  Valdayana inquired without opening her eyes.<br>
  &quot;Your family doesn't like you do they?&quot;  Millikin kneeled down beside her. <br>
  &quot;Aside from Elegy, my family is dead.  Does that answer your question?&quot;<br>
  &quot;That explains a lot.&quot;  Millikin looked at Valdayana intently who merely shrugged.  &quot;I don't know if I should feel sorry for you or wonder if it's the result of your karma.&quot;  Valdayana opened one eye and poked Millikin again.<br>
  &quot;Do not poke me.&quot;  Millikin whispered softly.<br>
  &quot;Then step back a pace maybe.&quot;  <br>
Millikin stood up and took a half step back, still watching her, contemplating.<br>
  &quot;I have studies to attend to, you know.&quot;  <br>
  &quot;What's so secretive that information is kept in books that are enchanted to keep others from reading them?&quot;<br>
  &quot;They aren't enchanted.  You simply can't understand them.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Letters don't move around on the pages of normal books.&quot;  Valdayana didn't respond, nor did Millikin really expect one.  Her thoughts turned to the different things she had experienced (good and bad) or learned in recent months directly or indirectly due to Valdayana's interference.  She pulled her hands out of her pocket as the enchanter stood up to leave.<br>
  &quot;Anyway, in case I never told you, thank you.&quot;  Millikin said quietly.<br>
  &quot;For?&quot;  <br>
  &quot;For what you've given me.  I'm not referring to tangible things though.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Good work, you're learning that knowledge is power.&quot;<br>
Millikin blinked in surprise.  &quot;I think that's the nicest thing you've ever said to me.&quot;<br>
  &quot;Don't get used to it.&quot;  Valdayana poked Millikin once more then walked away, leaving the ranger to her contemplations.<br>
